Introduction

Polio, once one of the worldâs most feared diseases, is now closer than ever to being eradicated, but the journey isnât over yet. Vaccination remains our most powerful tool to protect children and communities, ensuring that no life is left vulnerable to this preventable illness.

In this project, we explore real-world data sourced from UNICEF to examine how countries and regions around the world are performing in their efforts to immunize against polio. By analyzing trends, comparing regions, and investigating the relationship between life expectancy and vaccination rates, we aim to highlight where significant progress has been made and where greater efforts are still needed.

Using Python libraries such as pandas, seaborn, and matplotlib, we extract insights and create clear visualizations that tell the story behind the numbers. Through scatterplots, bar charts, maps, and tables, we uncover important patterns in global vaccination efforts from the top-performing countries to regions that continue to face challenges.

Beyond statistics and visualizations, this report provides an analytical overview of global polio vaccination efforts, highlighting performance variations across regions and examining the relationship between immunization rates and broader health indicators.

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)

EDA is the first step in any data project where we explore, clean, and understand the data to uncover important insights, identify anomalies, and set the foundation for further analysis or machine learning. We performed the following key operations to clean and prepare the datasets:

Step 1: Dropping Unnecessary Columns

Removed irrelevant columns from both âindicatorâ and âmetadataâ datasets to retain only the fields necessary for analysis.
This streamlines the datasets and avoids unnecessary noise during further processing.

Step 2: Converting Columns to Appropriate Data Types

Standardized data types across important columns: - Converted year fields (âtime_periodâ, âyearâ) to string format after parsing as dates. - Converted identifiers like âcountryâ, âalpha_3_codeâ, and âindicatorâ to string types. - Converted ânumeric_codeâ into integer type.

This ensures consistency and prevents type-related issues in future steps.

Step 3: Removing Data Before 1980

Filtered out entries before 1980 from âmetadataâ dataset to align with âindicatorâ dataset, which contains data starting from 1980 onwards.

Step 4: Removing Blank or Null Values

Dropped any rows containing missing or blank values in both datasets.
This ensures that further analysis is performed on complete and reliable data.

After completing these EDA steps, the datasets are now cleaner, more consistent, and ready for visualization.

Code 
#EDA step1: dropping unnecessary columns

indicator_df = indicator_df.drop(columns=['time_period_activity_related_to_when_the_data_are_collected',
                                          'unit_of_measure', 'unit_multiplier', 'observation_status',

#EDA step2: Convert the columns into appropriate datatypes

indicator_df['time_period'] = pd.to_datetime(indicator_df['time_period'], format='%Y').dt.strftime('%Y')
indicator_df['country'] = indicator_df['country'].astype(str)
indicator_df['numeric_code'] = indicator_df['numeric_code'].astype(int)
indicator_df['alpha_3_code'] = indicator_df['alpha_3_code'].astype(str)
indicator_df['indicator'] = indicator_df['indicator'].astype(str)
indicator_df['sex'] = indicator_df['sex'].astype(str)
indicator_df['current_age'] = indicator_df['current_age'].astype(str)

metadata_df['year'] = pd.to_datetime(metadata_df['year'], format='%Y').dt.strftime('%Y')
metadata_df['country'] = metadata_df['country'].astype(str)
metadata_df['alpha_3_code'] = metadata_df['alpha_3_code'].astype(str)

country_region_df['alpha_3_code']= country_region_df['alpha_3_code'].astype(str)
country_region_df['country'] = country_region_df['country'].astype(str)
country_region_df['region'] = country_region_df['region'].astype(str)

print("Columns successfully converted to appropriate datatypes")

# EDA step3: Remove the data before 1980 from metadata as we have data from 1980 onwards in the indicator file
metadata_df = metadata_df.loc[metadata_df['year'] >= '1980']

print("Data before 1980 successfully removed from metadata")

#EDA step4: Filter out rows with any blank or null values
indicator_df = indicator_df.dropna()
metadata_df = metadata_df.dropna()

Yet, the map also reveals stubborn inequalities: Central Africa, parts of the Middle East, and sections of South America remain behind, indicated by darker shades. This visualization reminds us that while vaccines have saved millions of lives globally, political instability, economic disparity, and misinformation continue to create pockets of risk. Itâs a call to action as the progress has been extraordinary, but true success will be when all the countries are covered and each child is vaccinated.

Visualization #2: Time-series Line Chart

Code 
# Creating time-series chart

time_series_df = (
    indicator_df.groupby("time_period", as_index=False)["obs_value"].mean()
)

# Calculate min, max, and mean of average obs_value
min_row = time_series_df.loc[time_series_df["obs_value"].idxmin()]
max_row = time_series_df.loc[time_series_df["obs_value"].idxmax()]
mean_value = time_series_df["obs_value"].mean()

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
ax = sns.lineplot(data=time_series_df, x="time_period", y="obs_value", marker="o")
plt.title("Average Polio Vaccination Over Time", fontsize=20, pad=30)
plt.xlabel("Year", fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel("Vaccination Rate (%)", fontsize=14)
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.grid(True)

#Adding annotations for min, max, and mean obs_value in the visualization
ax.text(
    min_row["time_period"], min_row["obs_value"],
    f"Min: {min_row['obs_value']:.1f}",
    ha="center", va="top", color="red", fontsize=12
)

ax.text(
    max_row["time_period"], max_row["obs_value"] + 2,
    f"Max: {max_row['obs_value']:.1f}",
    ha="center", va="bottom", color="green", fontsize=12
)

plt.axhline(mean_value, color="blue", linestyle="--", linewidth=1)
ax.text(
    time_series_df["time_period"].iloc[-1], mean_value + 1,
    f"Mean: {mean_value:.1f}",
    ha="right", va="bottom", color="blue", fontsize=12
)

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

This line graph captures the notable journey of global determination against one of humanityâs deadliest threats polio. In 1980, the world was in a dangerous place as just 48.3% of people were vaccinated on average. Yet, year after year, tireless efforts from local health workers to global campaigns pushed the immunization rate upward, reflecting massive collective action. By 2014, the world reached an impressive 89.2% vaccination rate, an achievement symbolizing one of the greatest public health successes ever. The slight dips after 2019 show how fragile this progress can be when crises like pandemics disrupt healthcare systems and makes it unstable. This graph is more than data points; it is living proof that when the world unites behind a cause with science and persistence then all the goals can be achieved

Visualization #3: Bar Graph

Code 
# Creating horizontal bar chart

regional_avg = joined_df.groupby("region", as_index=False)["obs_value"].mean()

regional_avg = regional_avg.sort_values(by="obs_value", ascending=False)

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
ax = sns.barplot(
    data=regional_avg,
    y="region",
    x="obs_value",
    hue="region",
    dodge=False,
    palette="pastel",
    legend=False
)

plt.title("Regional Comparison of Polio Vaccination")
plt.xlabel("Vaccination Rate (%)")
plt.ylabel("Region")

for container in ax.containers:
    ax.bar_label(container, fmt='%.1f', label_type='edge', padding=3)

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

The bar chart shows average polio vaccination coverage across different UNICEF regions. Europe and Central Asia boast a 93.1% immunization rate, a testament to strong healthcare systems, consistent funding, and public trust in vaccines. In contrast, South Asia (76.5%) and Sub-Saharan Africa (76.4%) expose critical vulnerabilities where millions of children remain at risk of preventable disease. This visualization is powerful because it doesnât just show averages it shows us global health inequalities that require urgent attention. Vaccination should not be a privilege of geography; it must be a universal right.

Visualization #4: Table

Code 
# Identifying top 10 countries per region based on average obs_value

avg_obs_by_country = joined_df.groupby('country')['obs_value'].mean().reset_index()
avg_obs_by_country = avg_obs_by_country.sort_values('obs_value', ascending=False)

# Function to get top 10 countries per region
def get_top_10_per_region(df, region_col='region', country_col='country', value_col='obs_value'):
    top_10_countries = []
    for region in df[region_col].unique():

        region_df = df[df[region_col] == region]
        region_avg = region_df.groupby(country_col)[value_col].mean().reset_index()
        region_avg_sorted = region_avg.sort_values(by=value_col, ascending=False)
        top_10_countries.extend(region_avg_sorted.head(10)[country_col].tolist())

    return top_10_countries

# Use the function created above to get top 10 countries per region
top_countries = get_top_10_per_region(joined_df)

# Filter the joined_df to fetch top 10 country data
top_10_df = joined_df[joined_df['country'].isin(top_countries)]

# Calculate the average of obs_value and life_expectancy to use in creating the scatterplot
top_10_avg_df = top_10_df.groupby(['region', 'country']).agg({
    'obs_value': 'mean',
    'life_expectancy_at_birth_total_years': 'mean',
    'population_total': 'mean'
}).reset_index()
Code 
#Creating Table to show top-10 countries per region
top_10_avg_df_sorted = top_10_avg_df.copy()

# Rounding the avg obs_value and population_total to 2 decimal places
top_10_avg_df_sorted['obs_value'] = top_10_avg_df_sorted['obs_value'].round(2)
top_10_avg_df_sorted['population_total'] = top_10_avg_df_sorted['population_total'].round(2)

top_10_avg_df_sorted = top_10_avg_df_sorted.sort_values(['region', 'obs_value'])

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 6))
ax.axis('off')

table_data = top_10_avg_df_sorted[['region', 'country', 'obs_value','population_total']]
column_titles = ["Region", "Country", "Average Vaccination Rate (%)","Average Country Population"]

# Generate the table
table = ax.table(
    cellText=table_data.values,
    colLabels=column_titles,
    cellLoc='left',
    loc='center'
)

table.auto_set_font_size(False)
table.set_fontsize(10)
table.auto_set_column_width(col=list(range(len(column_titles))))
tab10_colors = sns.color_palette("tab10")
unique_regions = top_10_avg_df_sorted['region'].unique()
region_colors = {region: tab10_colors[i % len(tab10_colors)] for i, region in enumerate(unique_regions)}

for (row, col), cell in table.get_celld().items():
    if row == 0:
        cell.set_text_props(weight='bold', color='white')
        cell.set_facecolor('#4CAF50')
    else:
        region = table_data.iloc[row-1]['region']
        cell.set_facecolor(region_colors.get(region, '#ffffff'))

fig.text(
    0.5, 1.35,
    "Top 10 Performing Countries Per Region (by Avg Vaccination Rate)",
    ha='center',
    va='top',
    fontsize=16,
    fontweight='bold'
)

plt.subplots_adjust(top=0.85)
plt.show()

This table highlights the top 10 performing countries in each world region based on their average polio vaccination rates from 1980 to 2023. In addition to vaccination coverage, it also shows each countryâs average life expectancy and average total population during the same period.

From the table, we can observe: that Countries like Tonga, Cuba, and Sweden consistently achieved very high vaccination rates and developed regions (e.g., Europe, East Asia) generally show higher vaccination rates compared to others.

Some countries in South Asia and Sub-Saharan Africa show lower vaccination rates, highlighting regional gaps.

This visualization helps us quickly spot which countries maintained higher immunization coverage and gives an idea of their population scale over time.

Visualization #5: Scatterplot

Code 
# Creating Scatter plot

# Calculate trend line
slope, intercept, r_value, p_value, std_err = linregress(
    top_10_avg_df["life_expectancy_at_birth_total_years"],
    top_10_avg_df["obs_value"]
)

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 8))
sns.scatterplot(
    data=top_10_avg_df,
    x="life_expectancy_at_birth_total_years",
    y="obs_value",
    hue="region",
    palette="tab10",
    s=100,
    ax=ax
)

# Adding trend line calculated earlier
x_vals = np.array(ax.get_xlim())
y_vals = intercept + slope * x_vals
ax.plot(x_vals, y_vals, '--', color='black', linewidth=2)

ax.set_title("Life Expectancy vs. Average Vaccination Rate by Top 10 Countries Per Region", fontsize=18, pad=20)
ax.set_xlabel("Life Expectancy (Years)", fontsize=14)
ax.set_ylabel("Average Vaccination Rate (%)", fontsize=14)
ax.grid(True)
legend = ax.legend(title="Region", bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left')
plt.subplots_adjust(right=0.75)
top_countries = pd.concat([
    top_10_avg_df.nlargest(5, 'obs_value'),
    top_10_avg_df.nsmallest(5, 'obs_value')
])

for i, row in top_countries.iterrows():
    ax.text(
        row["life_expectancy_at_birth_total_years"] + 0.5,
        row["obs_value"] + 0.5,
        row["country"],
        fontsize=9,
        color='black'
    )

if slope > 0:
    message = "Trend: Higher life expectancy is associated\nwith higher Vaccination rates."
else:
    message = "Trend: Higher life expectancy is associated\nwith lower Vaccination rates."

fig.text(
    0.79, 0.63,
    message,
    ha='left',
    va='top',
    fontsize=10,
    bbox=dict(boxstyle="round,pad=0.5", facecolor="white", edgecolor="black")
)

plt.show()

This scatter plot delivers a notable message: vaccination is not just about preventing disease; it is directly tied to longer, healthier lives. The strong upward trend shows that countries with higher immunization rates also enjoy higher life expectancies. Nations like Sweden and Hungary cluster at the top, while lower-performing countries like Afghanistan, Pakistan, and Nepal fall behind, with both lower immunization rates and shorter lifespans. This relationship underlines a hard reality: vaccines donât just save lives in the short term they elevate entire nations by building healthier and more resilient societies. The data speaks clearly: expanding vaccination coverage is not just a healthcare strategy but also a foundation for social and economic development.

Conclusion

Together, these visualizations reveal a powerful story of progress, persistence, and unfinished business. The world map shows how vaccination has expanded across continents, saving millions of lives but also leaving clear gaps that must not be ignored. Regional comparisons highlight significant variations, where some areas have achieved near-universal coverage while others still struggle. The time series graph proves that through sustained global effort, dramatic improvements are possible, yet it also reminds us that progress can quickly stall without continued commitment. Finally, the scatter plot between life expectancy and immunization underscores a deeper truth: vaccines are not just about preventing illness; they are the building blocks of healthier, longer, and more prosperous societies.

The journey from 1980 to 2023 has been remarkable, but the data calls us to action as the future of global health will be defined not just by how far we have come, but by how determined we are to finish the mission and make a healthier environment to live in.
